**Your name (matching your application)David Kirsch**

**Your email addressdk.dkes@hotmail.com**

**Describe the most exceptional achievement in your professional career
so far. (max 200 words)Preventing Good Day Farm Louisiana from collapse.
When transitioning from proven Phase 2 infratsucture to completely new
Phase 3 infrastructure, where everything was tested independently but
never in symphony and under load. Our out-of-state C-Suite, who were
solely focused on exit strategy and driven by stakeholders who are
innocently ignorant of commercial cultivation operations, just saw
expensive new assets that would boost the valuation of the company.
Their directive was to shut down Phase 2 and commit to Phase 3. Terrible
idea. New equipment installed and verified by people with conflicts of
interest, then approved by others who don't understand how anything
works. I spent two months with my cultivation director and other key
personnel company-wide mapping failure scenarios to present sharp
analysis to leadership about what happens when these untested systems
fail under production load and what this means financially, and for our
limited geographical talent pool. After convincing, they allowed me to
keep 6 of the 20 Phase 2 rooms operational. Unfortunately, I was right.
Phase 3 failed. I had calculated a minimum viable production level -
enough to maintain revenue without layoffs or affecting employees,
vendors, or retail partners. 6 rooms kept GDF Louisiana alive.**

**If you could instantly solve one problem in your current company,
ignoring all constraints, what would it be and why? (max 200
words)There\'s a disconnect between my blueprint-style vision and
technical execution. I can architect sophisticated operational systems
like my Consensus AI app, but I\'m consistently building tools that
build tools because I lack the technical fluency to ensure success in my
implementations. I\'ve gotten to the finish line with several preceding
apps, but there\'s an emerging pattern. I can architect Consensus (AI
orchestration with unlimited memory, etc) to then build the more complex
Buildr app. Buildr needs to exist because I need a canvas style coding
conversation app that allows me to build enterprise grade applications.
This lack of fluency causes inefficiency. I can conceptualize clearly,
and I can collaborate with AI to build them, but I get slowed down by
common coding pitalls, error prevention, and debugging that someone with
more development knowledge would have navigated more smoothly. If this
inefficiency did not exist, my operational output would be incredible.**

**Describe any counter-intuitive insights or unique strategies you've
personally developed for prompting LLMs. (max 200 words)I\'ve discovered
default rules and pre-baked-in process compliance fail consistently when
I\'m attempting to architect large systems. So, to mitigate this I\'ve
created my own governance that I instruct the AI to follow instead, and
then build it within the architecture itself as well. My consensus app
enforces \'Seven Sacred Laws\': Zero-regret - complete reversibility,
sacred contract (immutable interfaces), living memory (continuous
learning), token economy (cost as a core constraint), validation
requirements (multi-layer input validation), graceful degradation
(systematic fallback), and tribunal consensus (critical decisions
require multi-AI agreement). I think the counter-intuitive nature, here,
is treating these multiple AIs as a tribunal rather than individual
tools. Consensus orchestrates DeepSeek, GPT, and Claude with weighted
expertise domains that I continuously update as models evolve. DeepSeek
and Claude tend to lead on code, Claude for architecture/analysis, GPT
generally on creative tasks. In addition, I also wrote recipe-like
development prompts in YAML with constraints, patterns, and forbidden
elements pre-set. The goal is to eliminate all guessing,
interpretations, or assumptions - which in itself is also an instructive
protocol. Building these interruption mechanisms that detect token
thresholds, repetition patterns in patches/fixes, and quality
degradation before they become issues - obviously learning from past
catastrophes. This has effectively transitioned unreliable AI
collaboration and development into much more predictable, thoughtful
output.**

**What\'s the most interesting problem you\'re wrestling with in your
mind lately? Not necessarily work-related. (max 200 words)I often think
about economic displacement as a result of the velocity AI automation is
bringing to the world. Recently, I had a kind-of personal revelation
when I realized I can now effectively do the work of entire hired teams
through systematic AI collaboration. I\'m running three businesses that
require minimal oversight specifically because of how I\'ve leveraged
AI. This would not have been possible for me just 3 years ago. But this
personal achievement made me confront an uncomfortable question about
what happens when this scales - when more people understand it like I
do. History shows that economically successful countries tend to move
from goods-based to service-based economies, which displaces
manufacturing workers but created new service jobs over generations. Not
always in lock-step, but there\'s decades of overlap, nonetheless. The
issue I see is that AI automation is compressing what was a 50-year
economic transition into maybe 5-10 years. The typical absorption
mechanisms - retraining programs, new job categories, social safety
nets - these can\'t adapt as quickly. I\'m not worried about the
eventual, inevitable state where AI does everything. I\'m wrestling with
the transition chaos. What happens during that 15-year period where AI
can handle 40%, 50%, even 60% of service jobs? Is there a solve for
that? Then, do we solve it or do enlist the help of AI to figure out the
problem we and it started. This paradox is interesting to think about.
Which movie will we end up in? Wall-E? Terminator? The Matrix? It\'s
interesting to think about.**

**What aspects of our culture resonate most deeply with you and why?
(max 200 words)Definitely an alignment on workplace theories. Flat
hierarchy where everyone matters, a type-of employee ownership/reward
system where company-wide successes are shared company-wide. This
promotes immense pride and loyalty. I always say, \"You\'re never going
to innovate for someone you hate\" and \"happy people make better
products.\" I love radical transparency - I\'ve always believed in that
and was further inspired when I read Ray Dalio\'s book \"Principles.\"
This veritas system of working where real value shines and false or
pseudo value becomes apparent makes me feel supported as opposed to
threatened. The energy I felt reading through Demand.io\'s mission,
ethos, values, etc - they made me shiver. It was everything I believe in
and how I run my businesses and manage my own teams. It\'s rare. But I
seem to have found like minded people. People who seem to be
high-output, wide knowledge footprint individuals who are driven to
identify and fill business gaps without ego. What a dream. Outcomes over
tasks is ideal. GDF was a corporate bureaucratic nightmare that enforced
that I manage my teams in a traditional 9-5 sense where arbitrary and
often ambiguous KPIs and other metrics are applied that have no real
business impact, but look good to show off to investors for the next
cap-call. 93 grams per sqft sounds great, and it is - but is it good?
Will it sell? No. No it won\'t.**

**What's your ideal in-office vs remote work schedule? Are you situated
for a reasonable daily commute to our Santa Monica location? If not,
describe your relocation plans, and any timing or logistical
constraints. (max 200 words)I\'m in Simi Valley and I\'m happy to
commute through the worst of it - I\'m committed. I\'ve often driven
1.5+ hours one way. It actually allows me time to buffer between home
and work. I love driving, so, no issue there. That said, I would prefer
to not be stuck in traffic in the early morning. If 9 or 10am is
acceptable to avoid morning traffic, that would be ideal rather than
coming in earlier. I like to take my son to school in the mornings, so
that timing would work well. I understand it\'s hybrid, but being the
CEO\'s right hand, I feel there may be less flexibility in my role
specifically as I imagine I would need to be pretty close to Michael
most of the time. I\'m not sure of Michael\'s expectations, and I\'m
happy to accommodate whatever that looks like. Outside of that, I thrive
in an outcomes-focused environment where accomplishments matter more
than hours logged. When Michael needs me in the office or when
collaboration requires it, I\'m there. When the work can be done
effectively from home, I\'m productive there too. I can also work from
Michael\'s residence if that makes collaboration easier. I\'m ultimately
flexible to whatever the role requires. That all said, I am already
planning on moving out of my current location eventually - just haven\'t
aligned anything yet, and I\'m still saving a bit of cash and waiting
for one of my properties in Louisiana to sell. Once that happens, I have
zero problem relocating much closer to Santa Monica.**
